passages.text: Equity Market Review

With Bayrou likely to go, we think Macron will appoint a new PM and try to muddle through, rather than call fresh elections or resign. So spike in risk premia likely largely over for now. EU political noise reinforces US leadership, already helped by Fed & Al, but don't write- off Europe just yet.
France - bis repetita. PM Bayrou has called a confidence vote for 8 September, just ahead of budget negotiations in parliament and a nationwide day of protest on 10
September. We think his survival chances are slim

(see Mounting risks, 25 Aug), as he lacks a parliamentary majority, and both the far right (RN) and the left- wing (NFP) have confirmed they will vote against him. If that were to be the case, we see three potential scenarios: 1) the most probable one is for President Macron to appoint a new PM, as he did with Bayrou after Barnier's government collapsed in December, but this time around from his own camp. The new PM would be tasked with drafting the budget, which may take some time and result in less fiscal tightening; 2) Macron dissolves the national assembly and calls new elections, as he did in June last year. We think this is unlikely, given the strong showing of RN in the polls, although not impossible and increasingly part of the debate; 3) Macron resigns and triggers an early Presidential election, which we see as the least likely. We had warned investors about rising political/fiscal risk in France (see Germany vs. France divide, 30 Jun), and indeed Bayrou's decision took markets off guard this week. But complacency has quickly gone: the OAT- Bund spread is hovering near 80bp, up from 65bp a few days ago, French CDS are close to June'24 snap election highs, CAC is down \(\sim 3\%\) , our French domestic basket (BCEUFROD) down \(\sim 7\%\) , and MSCI France P/E relative is close to the lows again. If the first scenario materialises, we think risk premia are most likely to come down from here, with the OAT- Bund spread getting \(\frac{1}{2}\) or to 70bp, and a small rebound in equities. If Macron were to call a new election, the spread would likely get near 90bp again, which may result in 2- 3% additional downside for the breakeven index and more for domestics. The most disruptive scenario would likely be Macron to step down, taking the spread close to 100bp and domestic stocks down double digits. Overall, we think the first scenario is the most likely, so would be buying the dip. But no need to rush, and we expect a bumpy ride ahead, with a tricky path into the 2027 presidential election likely to keep French risk premia elevated. So we think investors could consider hedging political risk in domestic sectors like banks with exporters like Luxury) and could consider French exporters, in CAC, vs domestic names.

US leadership reinforced, but don't write- off Europe just yet. After tariff- driven headwinds, domestic political noise is resurfacing in Europe. Alongside the French drama, the Dutch government narrowly survived a similar motion this week. In Germany, tensions within the ruling CDU/CSU- SPD coalition are reportedly rising, with speculation about a potential split and the formation of a minority government. Meanwhile, in the US, Big Tech continues to deliver strong fundamentals, and Nvidia's results underscored robust AI capex spending (see Networking Shines as China Remains Unresolved, 27 Aug). Non- tech US equities have also benefited from the Fed put following Jackson Hole, contributing to a broadening of the rally into laggards and renewed US outperformance vs. Europe. Arguably, with US relative valuation back to the highs and positioning more extended too (see Who Owns What Fed put unleashed, 27 Aug), it may not be all smooth sailing in the US. Concerns over the Fed independence may play with FX and rate market nerves, and while our economists maintain that a September rate cut is the base case, strong payrolls and/or sticky inflation may still shift the Fed's reaction function, with a lot of dovishness in the price now. So we think diversification through Europe has merits, as its relative valuations are back near historical lows, even as activity remains resilient and political noise seems manageable.

Equity flows surged to \(\) 16.6b\(this week, a sharp increase from\) \ \(3bn\) previously. Inflows were broad- based across regions: US equities attracted \(\) 8.5bn\(, Global funds\) \ \(5.8bn\) , and EM\ \(3.0bn. However, this masked\) \ \(1.2bn\) of outflows from Europe.
All sectors globally saw inflows, led by Financials, followed by Technology and Materials. In Europe, Financials and Energy recorded inflows, while Industrials and Technology experienced outflows.

Fixed income funds extended their strong run, marking over four consecutive months of inflows. This week, US treasuries and IG saw inflows, while HY posted outflows for the second week in a row. In Europe, IG led inflows, followed by govies, with HY seeing modest inflows. MM funds saw \(\) 6.8bn\$ inflows this week, making it four weeks of inflows.

Year- to- date, MM funds stay around \(\) 638bn\(on the back of strong inflows recently. Fixed income funds around the\) \ \(468bn\) mark, on sustained inflows. Equities remain distant third with inflows of \(\sim\) 378bn.
